1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,219
You are arrested.

2
00:00:01,219 --> 00:00:04,064
Before you are even in the car,

3
00:00:04,064 --> 00:00:07,315
an officer reaches into your pocket and takes

4
00:00:07,315 --> 00:00:09,754
out your phone — your messages,

5
00:00:09,754 --> 00:00:12,598
your photos, your location, the record of

6
00:00:12,598 --> 00:00:14,630
almost everything you do .

7
00:00:14,630 --> 00:00:17,882
Can the police simply open it and start

8
00:00:17,882 --> 00:00:18,932
reading?

9
00:00:18,932 --> 00:00:21,370
For most of the smartphone era,

10
00:00:21,370 --> 00:00:22,996
the answer was unclear.

11
00:00:22,996 --> 00:00:26,247
Then, in 2014, the Supreme Court gave an

12
00:00:26,247 --> 00:00:29,498
answer so blunt it became famous: if the

13
00:00:29,498 --> 00:00:31,936
police want to search your phone,

14
00:00:31,936 --> 00:00:32,918
get a warrant .

15
00:00:33,334 --> 00:00:36,255
For two hundred years, the law had a

16
00:00:36,255 --> 00:00:38,810
simple rule: when the police arrest you,

17
00:00:38,810 --> 00:00:41,731
they can search what is on you —

18
00:00:41,731 --> 00:00:44,287
your pockets, your wallet, whatever you are

19
00:00:44,287 --> 00:00:46,477
carrying — without a warrant .

20
00:00:46,477 --> 00:00:49,398
It made sense when "what you are carrying"

21
00:00:49,398 --> 00:00:50,858
meant a few objects.

22
00:00:50,858 --> 00:00:53,779
But the device in your pocket is not

23
00:00:53,779 --> 00:00:54,829
an object.

24
00:00:54,829 --> 00:00:57,750
It is a window into your entire life.

25
00:00:57,750 --> 00:01:00,671
Over the next twelve minutes: the traffic stop

26
00:01:00,671 --> 00:01:03,592
that put that question in front of the

27
00:01:03,592 --> 00:01:06,147
Supreme Court, and the moment the Court

28
00:01:06,147 --> 00:01:08,703
decided that a smartphone is different from

29
00:01:08,703 --> 00:01:10,939
anything a person has ever carried before.

30
00:01:11,354 --> 00:01:14,392
In 2009, a man named David Riley is

31
00:01:14,392 --> 00:01:16,290
pulled over in San Diego,

32
00:01:16,290 --> 00:01:17,340
California.

33
00:01:17,340 --> 00:01:20,377
The initial reason is ordinary: he is driving

34
00:01:20,377 --> 00:01:23,415
on a suspended license, and his car is

35
00:01:23,415 --> 00:01:24,643
going to be impounded .

36
00:01:25,058 --> 00:01:26,997
When officers search the car,

37
00:01:26,997 --> 00:01:28,935
they find firearms hidden inside.

38
00:01:28,935 --> 00:01:30,098
Riley is arrested.

39
00:01:30,098 --> 00:01:33,200
And during that arrest, an officer takes the

40
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:35,914
smartphone out of his pocket and begins

41
00:01:35,914 --> 00:01:37,465
looking through it .

42
00:01:37,880 --> 00:01:40,923
What the officer finds goes far beyond the

43
00:01:40,923 --> 00:01:41,973
traffic stop.

44
00:01:41,973 --> 00:01:45,016
There are photos, videos, and contacts on the

45
00:01:45,016 --> 00:01:48,059
phone, and some of them appear to connect

46
00:01:48,059 --> 00:01:51,102
Riley to a street gang and to an

47
00:01:51,102 --> 00:01:52,243
earlier shooting .

48
00:01:52,243 --> 00:01:54,906
Later, at the station, a detective goes

49
00:01:54,906 --> 00:01:57,568
through the phone again, in more detail,

50
00:01:57,568 --> 00:02:00,611
building a case from what is stored inside

51
00:02:00,611 --> 00:02:01,661
it.

52
00:02:01,661 --> 00:02:04,126
None of this is done with a warrant

53
00:02:04,126 --> 00:02:04,926
.

54
00:02:04,541 --> 00:02:06,894
Using the evidence from the phone,

55
00:02:06,894 --> 00:02:09,246
prosecutors charge Riley in connection with

56
00:02:09,246 --> 00:02:12,383
the shooting — a far more serious matter

57
00:02:12,383 --> 00:02:15,127
than how he was first stopped .

58
00:02:15,543 --> 00:02:18,052
Riley's case travels to the Supreme Court

59
00:02:18,052 --> 00:02:20,919
alongside a second one, very different on the

60
00:02:20,919 --> 00:02:21,969
surface.

61
00:02:21,969 --> 00:02:24,836
A man named Brima Wurie is arrested in

62
00:02:24,836 --> 00:02:27,704
a drug case, and police use the call

63
00:02:27,704 --> 00:02:30,571
log on his simple flip phone to find

64
00:02:30,571 --> 00:02:31,646
an address .

65
00:02:31,646 --> 00:02:33,796
One case is a modern smartphone,

66
00:02:33,796 --> 00:02:35,947
the other an old flip phone.

67
00:02:35,947 --> 00:02:38,814
Together, they force the Court to answer a

68
00:02:38,814 --> 00:02:40,965
single, growing question: when the police

69
00:02:40,965 --> 00:02:43,832
arrest you, is the phone in your pocket

70
00:02:43,832 --> 00:02:46,366
just one more thing they are allowed to

71
00:02:46,366 --> 00:02:47,166
search?

72
00:02:46,781 --> 00:02:48,883
To see why this was hard,

73
00:02:48,883 --> 00:02:51,686
you have to understand a rule called "search

74
00:02:51,686 --> 00:02:52,737
incident to arrest."

75
00:02:53,153 --> 00:02:56,169
For a long time, the courts have allowed

76
00:02:56,169 --> 00:02:58,808
police, when they make a lawful arrest,

77
00:02:58,808 --> 00:03:01,825
to search the person and the area within

78
00:03:01,825 --> 00:03:04,841
their reach — without a separate warrant .

79
00:03:04,841 --> 00:03:06,350
The reasons are practical.

80
00:03:06,350 --> 00:03:09,366
First, officer safety: the police need to make

81
00:03:09,366 --> 00:03:12,383
sure you are not reaching for a weapon.

82
00:03:12,383 --> 00:03:15,022
Second, preserving evidence: they need to stop

83
00:03:15,022 --> 00:03:18,039
you from destroying something before it can be

84
00:03:18,039 --> 00:03:18,793
collected .

85
00:03:19,208 --> 00:03:22,311
Under that rule, courts had upheld searches of

86
00:03:22,311 --> 00:03:25,026
the things people carry — a wallet,

87
00:03:25,026 --> 00:03:27,353
a pocket, a crumpled cigarette package.

88
00:03:27,353 --> 00:03:30,068
So the government's argument in Riley was

89
00:03:30,068 --> 00:03:31,118
straightforward.

90
00:03:31,118 --> 00:03:34,221
A phone, it said, is just another item

91
00:03:34,221 --> 00:03:36,936
found on the person during an arrest.

92
00:03:36,936 --> 00:03:40,039
If the police can look inside a wallet,

93
00:03:40,039 --> 00:03:42,091
why not the phone next to it?

94
00:03:42,507 --> 00:03:45,601
But the Court looked harder at what a

95
00:03:45,601 --> 00:03:46,761
phone actually is.

96
00:03:46,761 --> 00:03:49,854
A wallet holds a few cards and photos.

97
00:03:49,854 --> 00:03:52,948
A modern smartphone holds tens of thousands of

98
00:03:52,948 --> 00:03:55,268
messages, years of photographs, a browsing

99
00:03:55,268 --> 00:03:57,202
history, a calendar, location records,

100
00:03:57,202 --> 00:04:00,295
and access to even more data stored in

101
00:04:00,295 --> 00:04:01,455
the cloud .

102
00:04:01,455 --> 00:04:04,549
The two are not the same kind of

103
00:04:04,549 --> 00:04:07,643
thing, the Court said — not in how

104
00:04:07,643 --> 00:04:10,736
much they hold, and not in what that

105
00:04:10,736 --> 00:04:11,510
holding reveals.

106
00:04:11,925 --> 00:04:14,714
And much of what a phone reaches is

107
00:04:14,714 --> 00:04:16,805
not even stored on the phone.

108
00:04:16,805 --> 00:04:19,594
Tap an app and you may be looking

109
00:04:19,594 --> 00:04:22,383
at data that lives on a company's servers,

110
00:04:22,383 --> 00:04:23,433
somewhere else entirely.

111
00:04:23,433 --> 00:04:25,873
By 2014, searching the device could quietly

112
00:04:25,873 --> 00:04:28,662
become a search of a life that is

113
00:04:28,662 --> 00:04:31,450
kept half in your pocket and half in

114
00:04:31,450 --> 00:04:32,492
the cloud .

115
00:04:32,907 --> 00:04:35,645
And the old justifications did not fit.

116
00:04:35,645 --> 00:04:38,773
The data inside a phone cannot be used

117
00:04:38,773 --> 00:04:41,902
as a weapon; it cannot cut an officer

118
00:04:41,902 --> 00:04:44,248
or help a suspect escape .

119
00:04:44,248 --> 00:04:47,376
The fear of evidence being destroyed could be

120
00:04:47,376 --> 00:04:50,114
handled in other ways, like securing the

121
00:04:50,114 --> 00:04:51,164
device.

122
00:04:51,164 --> 00:04:53,119
Strip away those two reasons,

123
00:04:53,119 --> 00:04:56,247
and what was left was simply the government

124
00:04:56,247 --> 00:04:58,985
wanting to read a person's entire digital

125
00:04:58,985 --> 00:05:02,113
life, on the spot, because they happened to

126
00:05:02,113 --> 00:05:02,627
be under arrest.

127
00:05:03,043 --> 00:05:05,387
In 2014, the Supreme Court ruled,

128
00:05:05,387 --> 00:05:07,731
and not one justice dissented .

129
00:05:07,731 --> 00:05:10,856
The opinion was written by Chief Justice John

130
00:05:10,856 --> 00:05:13,981
Roberts, and its core was simple: the police

131
00:05:13,981 --> 00:05:16,716
generally may not search the digital contents

132
00:05:16,716 --> 00:05:19,841
of a cell phone seized during an arrest

133
00:05:19,841 --> 00:05:21,403
without a warrant .

134
00:05:21,819 --> 00:05:25,269
Roberts wrote that modern phones are now such

135
00:05:25,269 --> 00:05:28,719
a pervasive and insistent part of daily life

136
00:05:28,719 --> 00:05:31,306
that they hold, in digital form,

137
00:05:31,306 --> 00:05:33,463
the privacies of life .

138
00:05:33,463 --> 00:05:36,913
The sum of an individual's private life can

139
00:05:36,913 --> 00:05:40,362
be reconstructed from the device — where they

140
00:05:40,362 --> 00:05:42,519
have been, who they know,

141
00:05:42,519 --> 00:05:45,106
what they believe, what they fear.

142
00:05:45,106 --> 00:05:47,262
A search of a phone,

143
00:05:47,262 --> 00:05:50,712
he said, is not like emptying a pocket.

144
00:05:51,128 --> 00:05:52,889
Roberts pushed the point further.

145
00:05:52,889 --> 00:05:54,650
A search of a phone,

146
00:05:54,650 --> 00:05:57,468
he wrote, is not just larger than a

147
00:05:57,468 --> 00:06:00,286
search of a wallet — it can be

148
00:06:00,286 --> 00:06:02,751
more revealing than the most thorough search

149
00:06:02,751 --> 00:06:03,808
of a house.

150
00:06:03,808 --> 00:06:06,626
Your home does not carry a record of

151
00:06:06,626 --> 00:06:09,091
everywhere you have been, everything you have

152
00:06:09,091 --> 00:06:11,909
searched for, and every message you have ever

153
00:06:11,909 --> 00:06:12,959
sent.

154
00:06:12,959 --> 00:06:14,727
The phone in your pocket does .

155
00:06:15,143 --> 00:06:17,911
The Court did not say the police can

156
00:06:17,911 --> 00:06:20,333
never see what is on your phone.

157
00:06:20,333 --> 00:06:23,102
It said they have to do what the

158
00:06:23,102 --> 00:06:24,832
Constitution normally requires for something

159
00:06:24,832 --> 00:06:26,908
this private: go to a judge,

160
00:06:26,908 --> 00:06:29,676
show probable cause, and get a warrant .

161
00:06:29,676 --> 00:06:32,445
The ruling came down to three words that

162
00:06:32,445 --> 00:06:35,213
are now quoted constantly: get a warrant .

163
00:06:35,629 --> 00:06:37,744
This was not a brand-new idea.

164
00:06:37,744 --> 00:06:40,566
It rested on a principle the Court had

165
00:06:40,566 --> 00:06:43,387
set out decades earlier, in a case about

166
00:06:43,387 --> 00:06:45,503
a man in a phone booth.

167
00:06:45,503 --> 00:06:48,324
There, the Court had held that the Fourth

168
00:06:48,324 --> 00:06:50,792
Amendment protects people, not places — that

169
00:06:50,792 --> 00:06:53,614
what you reasonably try to keep private stays

170
00:06:53,614 --> 00:06:56,082
protected, even out in the world .

171
00:06:56,082 --> 00:06:58,903
Riley took that principle and carried it into

172
00:06:58,903 --> 00:06:59,953
the smartphone.

173
00:06:59,953 --> 00:07:02,774
Your phone is not a place the police

174
00:07:02,774 --> 00:07:03,832
have walked into.

175
00:07:03,832 --> 00:07:06,654
It is the most concentrated record of you

176
00:07:06,654 --> 00:07:07,719
that has ever existed.

177
00:07:08,135 --> 00:07:11,358
It is also why the Court took two

178
00:07:11,358 --> 00:07:12,567
phones, not one.

179
00:07:12,567 --> 00:07:15,791
Riley's was a modern smartphone; Wurie's was a

180
00:07:15,791 --> 00:07:17,000
basic flip phone.

181
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,820
By deciding them together, the justices made

182
00:07:19,820 --> 00:07:23,044
clear the rule was not about how advanced

183
00:07:23,044 --> 00:07:24,253
your device is.

184
00:07:24,253 --> 00:07:27,476
The protection attaches to the phone as a

185
00:07:27,476 --> 00:07:30,297
category — the thing almost everyone now

186
00:07:30,297 --> 00:07:33,520
carries — not to the model in your

187
00:07:33,520 --> 00:07:34,326
hand .

188
00:07:34,742 --> 00:07:37,495
The Court left one important door open.

189
00:07:37,495 --> 00:07:40,248
In a true emergency — a bomb,

190
00:07:40,248 --> 00:07:43,395
a kidnapping, a child in danger — the

191
00:07:43,395 --> 00:07:46,541
police can still act without waiting for a

192
00:07:46,541 --> 00:07:47,591
warrant .

193
00:07:47,591 --> 00:07:49,558
The rule protects your phone.

194
00:07:49,558 --> 00:07:52,441
It does not turn it into a shield.

195
00:07:52,857 --> 00:07:55,856
Riley was the first time the Supreme Court

196
00:07:55,856 --> 00:07:58,481
looked squarely at the smartphone and said:

197
00:07:58,481 --> 00:07:59,981
this changes things .

198
00:07:59,981 --> 00:08:02,605
The old rules, written for pockets and

199
00:08:02,605 --> 00:08:05,605
wallets, could not simply be stretched over a

200
00:08:05,605 --> 00:08:07,855
device that holds your entire life.

201
00:08:08,270 --> 00:08:10,935
But notice how careful the ruling is.

202
00:08:10,935 --> 00:08:13,980
It protects the contents of the phone —

203
00:08:13,980 --> 00:08:17,025
the messages, the photos, the files you can

204
00:08:17,025 --> 00:08:18,928
see when you unlock it.

205
00:08:18,928 --> 00:08:21,973
It assumes the private thing is the data

206
00:08:21,973 --> 00:08:23,876
you put there on purpose.

207
00:08:23,876 --> 00:08:26,541
And it still leaves room for emergencies,

208
00:08:26,541 --> 00:08:29,586
for consent, and for the warrant the police

209
00:08:29,586 --> 00:08:31,869
can always go and get .

210
00:08:32,285 --> 00:08:35,183
Think about what is actually on the device

211
00:08:35,183 --> 00:08:36,632
the Court was protecting.

212
00:08:36,632 --> 00:08:38,443
Not only photos and messages,

213
00:08:38,443 --> 00:08:41,341
but the apps that quietly reveal the most

214
00:08:41,341 --> 00:08:44,239
private corners of a life — what you

215
00:08:44,239 --> 00:08:46,050
pray to, who you love,

216
00:08:46,050 --> 00:08:48,948
what illness you are reading about at two

217
00:08:48,948 --> 00:08:50,034
in the morning.

218
00:08:50,034 --> 00:08:52,932
The Court did not need to catalog every

219
00:08:52,932 --> 00:08:53,982
one.

220
00:08:53,982 --> 00:08:56,156
It only had to see that,

221
00:08:56,156 --> 00:08:58,366
taken together, they add up to you .

222
00:08:58,781 --> 00:09:01,785
What it does not fully answer is the

223
00:09:01,785 --> 00:09:03,287
harder question hiding underneath.

224
00:09:03,287 --> 00:09:06,291
Your phone does not only hold what you

225
00:09:06,291 --> 00:09:08,169
choose to put in it.

226
00:09:08,169 --> 00:09:11,173
Just by being on, it is constantly creating

227
00:09:11,173 --> 00:09:14,177
new information about you — and handing it

228
00:09:14,177 --> 00:09:15,303
to someone else.

229
00:09:15,303 --> 00:09:18,308
Every few minutes, it tells the nearest tower

230
00:09:18,308 --> 00:09:19,434
where it is.

231
00:09:19,434 --> 00:09:20,936
You never type that.

232
00:09:20,936 --> 00:09:22,438
You never see it.

233
00:09:22,438 --> 00:09:25,442
And it does not stay in your pocket

234
00:09:25,442 --> 00:09:28,446
— it goes straight to your phone company.

235
00:09:28,862 --> 00:09:31,274
Riley protected what is inside the device.

236
00:09:31,274 --> 00:09:34,031
The next case would ask who owns the

237
00:09:34,031 --> 00:09:35,754
trail the device leaves behind.

238
00:09:36,170 --> 00:09:39,145
David Riley's case began with a traffic stop

239
00:09:39,145 --> 00:09:42,120
and ended with a rule that touches everyone

240
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:43,608
who carries a phone.

241
00:09:43,608 --> 00:09:46,211
After 2014, the most personal object most

242
00:09:46,211 --> 00:09:49,187
people own could not be cracked open by

243
00:09:49,187 --> 00:09:51,790
the police just because they had been

244
00:09:51,790 --> 00:09:52,840
arrested.

245
00:09:52,840 --> 00:09:55,137
For that, the police need a warrant .

246
00:09:55,553 --> 00:09:58,660
But the protection had an edge to it.

247
00:09:58,660 --> 00:10:01,767
It guarded the words and images you placed

248
00:10:01,767 --> 00:10:04,874
inside the phone — the things you knew

249
00:10:04,874 --> 00:10:05,924
were private.

250
00:10:05,924 --> 00:10:09,031
It said much less about the information the

251
00:10:09,031 --> 00:10:10,973
phone produces on its own,

252
00:10:10,973 --> 00:10:13,303
automatically, and sends away without asking

253
00:10:13,303 --> 00:10:13,418
you.

254
00:10:13,834 --> 00:10:16,772
And the most revealing of all those automatic

255
00:10:16,772 --> 00:10:17,874
records is location.

256
00:10:17,874 --> 00:10:19,710
Your phone keeps a quiet,

257
00:10:19,710 --> 00:10:21,914
continuous log of where you are,

258
00:10:21,914 --> 00:10:24,852
day and night, and stores it with your

259
00:10:24,852 --> 00:10:25,902
carrier.

260
00:10:25,902 --> 00:10:28,841
If the police want that map of your

261
00:10:28,841 --> 00:10:31,779
life, do they need a warrant — or

262
00:10:31,779 --> 00:10:34,717
did you give it away the moment you

263
00:10:34,717 --> 00:10:35,504
turned the phone on?

264
00:10:35,919 --> 00:10:38,368
In 2018, the Court finally answered.

265
00:10:38,368 --> 00:10:40,000
That is next time.
